    <text xml:space="preserve">
      <body>
			<div type="edition" xml:lang="pyx-Latn">
				<ab>
					<lb n="1"/><seg type="siddham"/>
					<g type="ddanda">.</g>
					ḅay·ṁḥ dak·ṃ viy·ṃṁ
					tim·ṁ
					mlik· °o saḥ tgaṃ knon· °o <unclear reason="damage">p</unclear>li 
					<lb n="2"/>
					ḅay·ṁḥ
					luṅ·
					ḅa hi °o lup· yaṁ <g>•|•|</g><seg type="siddham-inverted"/>
					<!-- AG2MM: we had @||@ in rtf, but I am now skeptical of those dots. Could they be accidental? In any case, there is clearly an inverted siddham. Encoding adjusted but still uncertain on the two cases of •.  -->
					<!-- AG: in discussion with EM, she proposes to add @certainty and to use the character identifier in Unicode for the specifit bullet/dot we want to appear. And to enter <g ref="#siddham-inverted">, with definition in TEI header. -->
				</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="apparatus">
				<listApp>
					<app loc="1">
						<lem>tim·ṁ</lem>
						<note>We read <seg type="graphemic">t</seg> rather than <seg type="graphemic">n</seg> here, agreeing with Blagden and Tha Myat. If so, then <seg type="graphemic">tgaṃ</seg> can be correct too. If so, then <seg type="graphemic">t</seg> in this inscription would be of the “loop” type rather than the “cup” type seen in other inscriptions. But comparison with other inscriptions cautions us that even in a single inscription one may not necessarily expect a clear pattern in the distinction between <seg type="graphemic">t</seg> and <seg type="graphemic">n</seg>.</note>
					</app>
					<app loc="2">
						<lem>luṅ· … lup·</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">(nū) … nu</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tu+°o· … tu+p</rdg>
						<!-- MM2AG: following note is outdated now; should it be dropped? -->
						<!-- AG2MM: feel free to drop anything that is outdated. -->
						<note>There is no contrast in this inscription between “r with leftwards
							stroke” which we are interpreting as <seg type="graphemic">rū</seg> and
							“r with rightwards stroke” which in other inscriptions represents <seg type="graphemic">ru</seg>. Note also two slightly different shapes of <seg type="graphemic">rū</seg>, with and without loop at bottom; the first of them attested also in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00006">6</ref>, where it was interpreted as <seg type="graphemic">(bhūṃ)</seg> by Blagden; perhaps <seg type="graphemic">lu</seg> would be a possibility for shape with loop, but reading <seg type="graphemic">rū</seg> for shape without loop virtually guaranteed by occurrences of apparently related sequence <seg type="graphemic">°o ru kleḥ yaṁ</seg> at end of several urn inscriptions.</note>
					</app>
				<app loc="1">
						<lem>ḅay·ṁḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">baṁḥ</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">baṁḥ</rdg>
						</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>viy·ṃṁ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">vī</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">viṃṁ</rdg>
						<!-- MM: PR has viṁ in Burmese transliteration. -->
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>tim·ṁ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">ti</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tiṃṁ</rdg>
						<!-- MM: PR has tiṁ in Burmese transliteration. -->
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>mlik·</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">ṃ(l)i</rdg>
						<!-- MM: Blagden has initial ṃ which must be a typo. -->
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">mliṁ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>knon·</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">kño</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem><unclear reason="damage">p</unclear>li </lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">(ch) di</rdg>
						<!-- MM: Blagden's space between (ch) and di is a typo. -->
					</app><app loc="2">
						<lem>ḅay·ṁḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">bàḥ</rdg>
						<!-- MM: Blagden's grave accent is a typo for the superscript dot ṁ. -->
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">baṁḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="2">
						<lem>luṅ·</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">(nū)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tu+°o·</rdg>
					</app><app loc="2">
						<lem>ḅa</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">ba</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">ba</rdg>
					</app><app loc="2">
						<lem>lup·</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">nu</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tu+p·</rdg>
					</app></listApp>
			</div>
			<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<p>Julian K. Wheatley's translation of <bibl><ptr target="bib:ThaMyat1963_01"/><citedRange>21</citedRange></bibl></p>
				<ab>The structure (tomb) of the honorable Tubahi, the son of the honorable Davintinmrin and the grandson of Nagukano.</ab>
				<p><bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 75 n. 27</citedRange></bibl></p>
				<ab>These are the bones of the Honourable Ru-ba, deceased son of the Honourable La-wi: ni' mli (sic), grandson of Nga-kno.</ab>
				<p><bibl><ptr target="bib:Duroiselle1912_01"/></bibl></p>
				<ab>These are the bones of the deceased, Lord Rūḅa, grandson of Nga Kno, son of Lord Davinimli.</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="commentary">
<listApp>
			<app loc="1">
				<lem><unclear>p</unclear>li</lem>
				<note>Photos such as IMG_8373 favor initial <seg type="graphemic">p</seg> over <seg type="graphemic">m</seg>: <seg type="graphemic">pli</seg> 'grandson'.</note>
			</app>
			<app loc="2">
			<note>The sequence <seg type="graphemic">ḅa hi</seg> also attested in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00002">2</ref>.</note>
			</app>
</listApp>
			</div>
			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--ASB 1904-05, 8-9, 35; 1915, 21-3. — ASI 1904-05, 126; 1929-30, 152. — PR, 21.—PPPB I, 66, 75 n. 27, 149. — Shafer 1943: 339.-->
				<p>Reported in <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1913: 14-5</citedRange></bibl>, which includes a reading of the opening akṣaras. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01"/><citedRange> 127 (E)</citedRange></bibl> takes note of this urn, but focuses his study on the four (PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00003">3</ref>, <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00004">4</ref>, <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00005">5</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00006">6</ref>) that share reference to the Vikrama kings. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1915: 21-3</citedRange></bibl> provides complete readings and notes by Blagden and Sastri; in most respects, Sastri is not as compatible with our readings as Blagden. Luce, in <bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 65, 75 n. 24, 127</citedRange></bibl>, provides an overview and offers a modified reading. Re-edited here from published photographs.</p>
				<listBibl type="primary"><bibl><ptr target="bib:CPI2018_01"/><citedRange unit="item">DHARMA_INSPYU00001</citedRange></bibl></listBibl><listBibl type="secondary">
					<bibl><ptr target="bib:ASI"/><citedRange>1929-30, p. 152</citedRange></bibl>
					<bibl><ptr target="bib:Shafer1943_01"/><citedRange>339</citedRange></bibl>
					<bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinWin2016_01"/><citedRange>14-5</citedRange></bibl>
				</listBibl>
			</div>
		</body>
  </text>
